## What this is

This is the **Analog Elk reference instance** of Elk OS — the profile that makes
the system its own final test case: an agency using its CMS, agents,
constitution, and worktree discipline to build (and ship) the thing that ships
itself. Four subsystems boot together and stay wired:

1. **This Claude-side OS** — this file, the MCP server, the SessionStart hooks,
   the memory seed.
2. **Directus + the `os_*` schema** — the shared-state bus (tasks, sprints,
   projects, releases, repositories) that the human and the agent fleet both
   read and write. Single source of truth for work.
3. **A local RAG knowledge engine** — semantic search over docs; Claude is the
   only LLM, no external inference.
4. **The portal** — the human observability surface over the same data.

You (Claude) reach the shared bus through the **`elk-os-cms` MCP server**,
pointed at this deployment's own Directus at `{{DIRECTUS_URL}}`.

> Note: this is a self-contained deployment. It does **not** share credentials,
> client data, or infrastructure with any production Analog Elk system — the MCP
> server, hooks, and seed all target this instance's own Directus.

## 1. Work lands on the `os_tasks` board — always

The `os_tasks` collection is the shared substrate. The human watches it in the
portal; the agent fleet reads and writes it over MCP. **A required follow-up that
isn't finished by session end goes to `os_tasks` — never floating in chat.**

Set at minimum: `name` (imperative), `description` (Markdown: context / done /
left / file refs), `status` (`pending` | `in_progress` | `completed` — the last
only when shipped + verified), `priority` (`P0`–`P3`, default `P2`). Use the MCP
`items` tool for all board operations; call the MCP `system-prompt` tool first to
learn the live schema.

## 2. Never paste live tokens or secrets into chat

Secrets live only in the deployment `.env` (gitignored) and reach a session via
the environment — the MCP server reads `${DIRECTUS_ADMIN_TOKEN}` from the shell,
never from a committed file. A secret in chat is compromised; rotate it before
the session ends.

## 3. Branching: one trunk = production

One trunk per repo; the GitHub default branch MUST equal the production deploy
branch (`main`). Short-lived `feat/…`/`fix/…`/`chore/…` branches off the trunk,
squash-merge back, delete after. No second mainline. Confirm a PR's base is the
trunk before merging.

## 4. Versioning is automated — never hand-bump

Semver, bumped automatically from **Conventional Commit** messages by release
automation on merge to trunk (`feat:` → minor, `fix:`/`perf:` → patch,
`feat!:`/`BREAKING CHANGE` → major). Never edit `package.json` `version` by hand.
Every PR title / squash commit must be a valid Conventional Commit.

## 5. Document what ships (releases)

Record every meaningful batch as a `releases` row with a grouped markdown
changelog (Added / Changed / Fixed / Security / Breaking). It surfaces in the
portal Releases view. Don't leave shipped work undocumented.

## 6. Worktree discipline (when multiple agents share a repo)

When more than one session may touch the same repo, work in your **own isolated
worktree** off fresh `origin/main`; never edit feature code from a shared root
checkout that can switch under you. Before picking work, check active worktrees
and in-flight branches and don't collide with what another agent is building.

## 7. Closing a piece of work

When a non-trivial task is done, close the loop in both places: update its
`os_tasks` row (status + completion notes) so the human sees it; and if the
session learned something durable and non-obvious, record it in `.claude/memory/`
and add a one-line pointer to `.claude/memory/MEMORY.md`. That two-place close
makes the human <-> agent loop legible from either side.

## Where things are

- **Shared board (Directus):** `{{DIRECTUS_URL}}` — via the `elk-os-cms` MCP
